  "Which factor does NOT affect the margin of error?": "",
  "Confidence level": "",
  "Population size (when much larger than sample)": "",
  "Standard deviation of the data": "",
  "When the population is much larger than the sample (at least 10 times), the population size has virtually no effect on the margin of error.": "",
  "What does 'margin of error' mean?": "",
  "The number of errors made during data collection": "",
  "The percentage of incorrect responses in the sample": "",
  "The difference between the largest and smallest data values": "",
  "The maximum likely difference between the sample statistic and the true population parameter due to random sampling": "",
  "The margin of error quantifies the precision of a sample estimate by indicating the maximum expected distance between the statistic and the parameter due to random sampling variability.": "",
  "What does 'precision' mean in the context of estimation?": "",
  "The confidence level of the interval": "",
  "How close the estimate is to zero": "",
  "How close repeated estimates are to each other (related to the width of the confidence interval)": "",
  "The number of decimal places reported": "",
  "Precision refers to the closeness of repeated estimates to each other. A narrow confidence interval (small margin of error) indicates high precision.": "",
  "What is a 'critical value'?": "",
  "The most important data point in the sample": "",
  "The sample mean": "",
  "The smallest possible margin of error": "",
  "The z* or t* multiplier that corresponds to the chosen confidence level": "",
  "The critical value is the number of standard errors from the center needed to capture the desired percentage of the sampling distribution (e.g., z* = 1.96 for 95%).": "",
  "What does 'sampling variability' mean?": "",
  "Errors caused by biased sampling methods": "",
  "Variability caused by measurement tools": "",
  "The range of the population data": "",
  "The fact that different random samples from the same population produce different statistics": "",
  "Sampling variability is the natural variation in sample statistics from sample to sample. The margin of error is designed to account for this variability.": "",
  "What is 'systematic error' (bias)?": "",
  "Random fluctuations that cancel out with larger samples": "",
  "The standard error of the sample mean": "",
  "A consistent tendency to over- or underestimate the parameter, not reduced by increasing sample size": "",
  "The margin of error reported in polls": "",
  "Systematic error (bias) pushes estimates consistently in one direction and cannot be fixed by simply increasing sample size, unlike random sampling error.": "",
  "What does it mean to say ME is 'proportional to 1/sqrt(n)'?": "",
  "ME does not depend on sample size at all": "",
  "Quadrupling n cuts the ME in half (due to the square root relationship)": "",
  "Doubling n cuts the ME in half": "",
  "Increasing n increases the ME": "",
  "Because ME contains 1/sqrt(n), you need to multiply n by 4 to halve the ME. This square root relationship means diminishing returns from increasing sample size.": "",
  "What is the 'half-width' of a confidence interval?": "",
  "The margin of error, which is the distance from the center to either endpoint": "",
  "Half of the standard deviation": "",
  "Half of the sample size": "",
  "Half of the confidence level": "",
  "The half-width of a confidence interval is the margin of error. It is the distance from the point estimate (center) to either the upper or lower bound.": "",
  "What does 'diminishing returns' mean for sample size and margin of error?": "",
  "Each additional increase in sample size produces a progressively smaller reduction in margin of error": "",
  "At some point, increasing sample size increases the margin of error": "",
  "Larger samples always produce proportionally smaller margins of error": "",
  "Sample size has no effect on margin of error": "",
  "Due to the square root relationship, going from n=100 to n=400 halves the ME, but going from n=400 to n=1600 is needed for the next halving. Each unit of improvement costs more.": "",
  "What is the 'worst-case' proportion for planning sample size?": "",
  "p = 0.5, because it maximizes p(1-p) and gives the largest possible margin of error": "",
  "p = 1, because it represents certainty": "",
  "p = 0, because it minimizes the standard error": "",
  "p = 0.95, because it represents the confidence level": "",
  "When planning sample size with no prior estimate of the proportion, using p = 0.5 gives the most conservative (largest) sample size needed, ensuring the desired margin of error regardless of the true proportion.": "",
  "What is the 'finite population correction factor'?": "",
  "The ratio of sample size to confidence level": "",
  "A factor applied when the population is much larger than the sample": "",
  "A factor that increases the margin of error for small populations": "",
  "An adjustment that reduces the margin of error when the sample is a large fraction of the population": "",
  "When the sample is more than about 5-10% of the population, the finite population correction factor sqrt((N-n)/(N-1)) reduces the standard error and narrows the confidence interval.": "",
  "A university surveys 400 students and finds that 62% prefer online exams, with a margin of error of plus or minus 4.8% at 95% confidence. The administration wants the margin of error to be no more than plus or minus 2.4%. How many students should they survey?": "",
  "800": "",
  "200": "",
  "1,600": "",
  "1,200": "",
  "To halve the margin of error from 4.8% to 2.4%, they need to quadruple the sample size: 400 times 4 = 1,600 students.": "",
  "A news report states: 'According to our poll of 1,500 likely voters, the candidate has 47% support with a margin of error of plus or minus 2.5%.' A reader asks whether the candidate could actually have majority support (over 50%). What is the best answer?": "",
  "No, because 1,500 voters is too small for national polls": "",
  "No, because 47% is below 50%": "",
  "Yes, because the margin of error means the true value could be anything": "",
  "Yes, because the confidence interval extends to 49.5%, which is still below 50%, so majority support is unlikely but possible due to other errors": "",
  "The interval is (44.5%, 49.5%), which does not include 50%. Based on this data, majority support is unlikely, though the margin of error only accounts for sampling error, not other systematic issues.": "",
  "A market research firm surveys 500 consumers about a new product. They find 35% would buy it, with a margin of error of plus or minus 4.2%. Their client asks: 'If we surveyed 2,000 consumers instead, what would the margin of error be?' What is the approximate answer?": "",
  "Plus or minus 1.05%": "",
  "Plus or minus 2.1%": "",
  "Plus or minus 4.2% (unchanged)": "",
  "Plus or minus 8.4%": "",
  "Increasing from 500 to 2,000 is a factor of 4. Since ME is proportional to 1/sqrt(n), the new ME is approximately 4.2/sqrt(4) = 4.2/2 = 2.1%.": "",
  "Two polls on the same topic give different results: Poll A (n = 500) has ME = plus or minus 4.4%, and Poll B (n = 2,000) has ME = plus or minus 2.2%. Poll A shows 52% support and Poll B shows 49% support. Which result is more trustworthy, and can we say the results contradict each other?": "",
  "Both polls are equally trustworthy regardless of sample size": "",
  "Poll B is more precise due to its larger sample; the results do not necessarily contradict each other since their confidence intervals overlap": "",
  "Poll A is better because it shows higher support": "",
  "The polls contradict each other and both should be discarded": "",
  "Poll B has a smaller margin of error (more precise). Poll A's interval is (47.6%, 56.4%) and Poll B's is (46.8%, 51.2%). These overlap substantially, so the results are consistent.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company wants to estimate the mean blood pressure reduction from a new drug. From a pilot study, they estimate sigma = 8 mmHg. They want a 95% CI with a margin of error of plus or minus 1 mmHg. What sample size do they need?": "",
  "16": "",
  "246": "",
  "1,000": "",
  "62": "",
  "n = (z* times sigma / ME)^2 = (1.96 times 8/1)^2 = (15.68)^2 = 245.9. Round up to n = 246.": "",
  "A 95% confidence interval based on a sample of 100 has a margin of error of 5.0. A colleague argues that using a 90% confidence level instead would give a margin of error of about 4.2. Is she correct, and what is the trade-off?": "",
  "She is correct and there is no trade-off": "",
  "She is approximately correct (z* drops from 1.96 to 1.645, reducing ME by about 16%), but the trade-off is lower confidence in capturing the true parameter": "",
  "She is wrong; changing the confidence level does not affect the margin of error": "",
  "She is wrong; a 90% level would increase the margin of error": "",
  "The ratio of critical values is 1.645/1.96 = 0.839, so the new ME would be about 5.0 times 0.839 = 4.2. The trade-off is that 10% of such intervals (vs. 5%) would miss the true parameter.": "",
  "A local newspaper reports the results of a poll: '58% of residents favor the new park, with a margin of error of plus or minus 5%.' However, the poll was conducted by asking people leaving a fitness center. Why might the actual margin of error be misleading?": "",
  "The sample location does not affect poll results when the sample size is sufficiently large and properly weighted": "",
  "The reported margin of error only accounts for random sampling error, not the selection bias from surveying at a fitness center where people may disproportionately favor parks": "",
  "The margin of error already accounts for all sources of bias including selection effects and nonresponse patterns": "",
  "Plus or minus 5% is always accurate for any poll that uses a sample size of at least one thousand respondents": "",
  "The margin of error formula assumes random sampling. Sampling from a fitness center introduces selection bias (people who exercise may be more likely to favor a park), which the margin of error does not capture.": "",
  "A company's quality team measures the diameter of 50 bolts and finds a mean of 10.02 mm with s = 0.15 mm. They calculate a 95% CI of (9.977, 10.063) mm with a margin of error of 0.043 mm. The specification requires the mean diameter to be within 0.1 mm of 10.00 mm. Does the product meet specifications?": "",
  "No, because the sample mean is not exactly 10.00 mm": "",
  "No, because the margin of error is not zero": "",
  "More data is always needed before any conclusion": "",
  "Yes, because the entire 95% CI falls within the specification range of (9.90, 10.10) mm": "",
  "The CI (9.977, 10.063) falls entirely within the specification range (9.90, 10.10). This provides strong evidence that the true mean diameter meets the specification.": "",
  "A researcher has a budget that allows surveying exactly 600 people. She estimates the population proportion is near 0.3. What is the approximate margin of error for a 95% confidence interval?": "",
  "Plus or minus 8.0%": "",
  "Plus or minus 3.7%": "",
  "Plus or minus 1.2%": "",
  "Plus or minus 5.0%": "",
  "SE = sqrt(0.3 times 0.7 / 600) = sqrt(0.00035) = 0.0187. ME = 1.96 times 0.0187 = 0.0367, or approximately 3.7%.": "",
  "A national health survey with n = 10,000 reports that 23.5% of adults are obese, with a margin of error of plus or minus 0.8%. A state-level subsample of n = 500 from the same survey reports 28.1% obesity with a margin of error of plus or minus 3.9%. Why is the state estimate so much less precise despite coming from the same survey?": "",
  "State-level data is always less accurate than national data": "",
  "The state subsample is much smaller, so the margin of error is larger due to the 1/sqrt(n) relationship": "",
  "The confidence level was different for the state estimate": "",
  "The state used different questions": "",
  "With n = 500 vs. 10,000, the state subsample has sqrt(10000/500) = sqrt(20) = 4.47 times the standard error. This demonstrates why subgroup analyses have larger margins of error than overall estimates.": ""
